“Having fun, that’s the most important thing. You blink and these moments pass by. I’m so scared … but let’s just have fun.” —@raye (RAYE) 🌹💫 
 
Nothing, not even fear, will stop the talented force that is RAYE, who’s making record-breaking history at tonight’s @brits (BRIT Awards). The UK-based singer and songwriter is up for seven nominations, the most received by any artist in a single year, including Best New Artist, Artist of the Year and Album of the Year. 
 
She’s also already won Songwriter of the Year, making her the first woman to win in this category, and she’ll be performing at tonight’s show. Ahead of her big night, we went behind the scenes to see her get performance ready. 🤩 
 
“Me and high heels have a very love-hate relationship. I’m always like, ‘I’ll wear them for one picture and then take them off.’ But when I sing, I never wear them. I’m always barefoot.” 
 
The outfit is prepped, the hair is dyed, the vocal chords are warmed up, but the world isn’t ready for this performance. No further introduction needed. Get ready to be dazzled by RAYE at tonight’s #BRITS. ✨❤️✨ 
 
Music by @raye

“When packing for Mardi Gras, it’s important that you just start with the essentials,” says presenter, writer, podcaster and creator @louishanson (Louis Hanson). And those essentials are...? “My six wigs.” 🌈 ⁣
 ⁣
It’s the final weekend of Sydney Mardi Gras, and Louis is taking us along for his packing journey. While the weekend will be filled with colorful parades and parties, the celebrations really represent an especially meaningful moment for the LGBTQ+ community in Australia. ⁣
 ⁣
“Most important, it’s just about taking to the streets, showing up, being visible and being proud of who you are,” says Louis. ⁣
 ⁣

“Love for me has always been about that feeling of belonging. I really thrive on love — love for myself, and for my community.” —@williegreene_ (Willie Greene)⁣
 ⁣
When he was just 14 years old, Willie’s creative drive and ambitious dreams inspired him to launch @wetheurban (We The Urban), an online community that initially started as a blog of everything he deemed cool and quickly developed into a global phenomenon of self-expression. ⚡️⁣
 ⁣
“I realized at a really early age that the internet can be used as a tool to fuel creativity. Social media became my window and stage, a vast world where I could build my voice and find my community,” says Willie. “Yet in this digital age, where my words echo across screens to millions, I wrestle with the strangest paradox: the feeling of having my voice be a beacon to the modern world, yet feeling profound loneliness at times.”⁣
 ⁣
After over a decade of curating and uplifting others’ work, Willie is learning to embrace that feeling of loneliness and is turning it into a place of solace. “I’ve discovered the most intimate community of love there is — the one within me, a sacred space where I am both the thinker and the observer. And now I see just how much power there is in the world seeing me, this Black kid from the south who came from parents from humble beginnings, as the one inspiring them. I deserve to be here, I deserve to be seen. And people like me deserve to be in this space.” 💫⁣
 ⁣
This month, we’ve been celebrating Black history through sharing some of our favorite love stories ✨💕 #ShareBlackLove

“Don’t let other people hold you back from loving and expressing yourself in the way you are compelled. That’s something I try to stand by, whether I am doing a photo shoot, making music or creating a skit.” —Model, creator and musician @sarahlugor (Sarah Lugor) ⁣
 ⁣
“I really think it’s important to show people that their unique traits, talents and personalities should be embodied fully,” says Sarah, a first-generation South Sudanese American who was raised in Las Vegas.
 ⁣
Sarah has been called an LGBTQ+ trailblazer. “I think the best thing about being out online is the sense of strength and belonging I can share with others. I have always been searching for a community and I feel like I really found one when I started being myself online. I discovered a lot of confidence where I least expected it and a lot of the doubt started getting drowned out by those who saw the light in me.” ⁣
 ⁣
@sarahlugor is one of 24 young, unique, difference-makers and catalysts we love who is sparking the cultural zeitgeist. #24for24 🌈 ⁣
 ⁣
Photos by @sarahlugor

“I love surfing — being in the ocean and having a connection with nature. It’s one of the most beautiful things in life.” —Pro surfer @riowaida_ (Rio Waida) ⁣
 ⁣
Rio grew up in a surfer’s paradise: Bali, Indonesia. “I feel like Indonesia has the most perfect waves in the world, period. Every wave I ride makes me happy. But I’m a very competitive guy, so that’s why I take surfing seriously.” ⁣
 ⁣
Rio’s passion for surfing has taken him all the way to the Tokyo 2020 Olympics — and now he’s focused on qualifying for Paris 2024. “I want to become world champion and pick up a gold medal at the Olympics. That’s a very big mountain to climb, but everything is possible if you keep chasing and keep working hard.” ⁣
 ⁣
@riowaida_ is one of 24 young, unique, difference-makers and catalysts we love who is sparking the cultural zeitgeist. #24for24 🌊 ⁣
 ⁣
Photos of @riowaida_ by @raw._clip and @georgeswims

“Inspiring others to dance and enjoy life brings me so much joy.” —@nianaguerrero (Niana Guerrero) ⁣
 ⁣
“I discovered my passion for dance when I was really young,” says Niana, who grew up in Quezon City, Philippines. “I always found myself moving to the rhythm of any music that played at home or anywhere I went. It was a natural pull that I just couldn’t resist.” ⁣
 ⁣
Dance is very much a family affair for Niana, who often performs alongside her brother Ranz. “It’s the blend of our individual styles and the fun we have while performing that I enjoy the most,” she says. And all Niana needs to get her creativity flowing is music. “Whether it’s new music or from the 2000s, ‘90s, ‘80s and even older, as long as it has a good vibe and groove to it, I should be able to create something with it.” ⁣
 ⁣
@nianaguerrero is one of 24 young, unique, difference-makers and catalysts we love who is sparking the cultural zeitgeist. #24for24 ❤️‍🔥 ⁣
 ⁣
Video by @nianaguerrero

“Love feels like home. Home means peace, warmth, equilibrium. It feels like breathing.” 🤎🏠 ⁣
 ⁣
Welcome to the home of @skylarmarshai (Skylar Marshai) and @tolutemi (Temi Ibisanmi). The globe-trotting couple are known for documenting their epic adventures together — from her roots in Barbados to his native country of Nigeria, and over a dozen countries in between. They’re an unstoppable force, and though they discover elements of home in every corner of the world they visit, their favorite place is in the foundation of the home they’re building with each other. ⁣
 ⁣
“We always felt like home to each other, so creating a home with one another just made sense,” says Temi. “My happily-ever-after looks like yesterday and every day like it.” ⁣
 ⁣
Skylar agrees. “My happily-ever-after looks like this. Period.” ⁣
 ⁣
This month, we’re celebrating Black history through our favorite love stories ✨ #ShareBlackLove
